Q1) Principle of Least Privilege (10 Marks)
Definition
The Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) is a security concept where a user, application, or service is given only the minimum permissions required to perform its task and nothing more.

It reduces the chances of:

Unauthorized access

Data leakage

Accidental deletion

Malware spread

Insider attacks

How It Works
Suppose:

A developer only needs access to upload files to S3.

An auditor only needs to view files.

Then:

Developer gets Read + Write

Auditor gets Read-only

No admin access is provided.

Example in AWS IAM
User	Permission
Developer	Upload and read S3 objects
Auditor	Only read S3 objects
Intern	No access to production resources
Advantages
Improves security

Prevents misuse of resources

Reduces attack surface

Helps meet compliance requirements

Prevents accidental changes

Real-Time Example
In a company:

HR staff should access employee records only.

Finance staff should access billing systems only.

Developers should not access payroll databases.

This is Least Privilege.

